etymologies: early 17th century; earliest use found in John Chamberlain (1553–1628), letter writer. From post-classical Latin postnatus younger son, person born after the uniting of the Scottish and English crowns, use as noun of postnatus postnate

definitions: Chiefly in plural. A person born after a particular event; specifically in Scotland, one born after the uniting of the Scottish and English crowns (1603).
